ok, state your parameters.  Do you want to measure economic strength by GNP?  Growth?  Productivity?  Per person GNP?  Average income?  What are we talking about here?<br>
<br>
In case you're curious, go back to some of the discussions that were held about NAFTA.  YOu'll see that one of the reasons to create the NAFTZ was a response to the formation of the EU which would have made a bigger single economic unit than the US.  The creation of the NAFTZ made it into a larger free trade zone than the EU although it did not include the economic and political ties that the EU has.<br>
<br>
As far as the EU's unity, I dont know how to answer this.  How do you determine when a collection of individual political entities form a single political unit.  The EU has a single currency, a single body that supposedly makes political and economic decisions.  Does it work well?  Not really, but it does meet the definition of a political unit.  Again, if you want to argue further, please state your parameters of what defines a country.  Internal dissent does not work as a counter definition since many countries have factions which disagree with the central governing body.<br>
<br>
As far as weapons export.  AK-47's and 30 year old tanks do make a difference.  Curious to see what you believe the Iraqis are using.  Also, do you know that the planes that the US air force are flying are 30 years old?  F15 and 16's were both designed in the 70's...  Again, how do you want to frame this argument?  Do you want to go by dollar value?  Numbers?  Countries exported to?  <br>
<br>
The definition of a high tech weapon is somewhat vague.  In terms of equivalent tech levels, Russia exports way more than the US.  The US has a very strict system of monitoring who it exports weapons to, something I like very much.  Russia at this point will export weapons to any organization willing to cough up some dollars.  So yes, on the whole, they export more.  This is a positive aspect of the US as far as I can see.<br>
<br>
