<br>
ok, I'll work with your definition.<br>
<br>
In the US, local matters are decided by state governments.  My apologies if I dont recall the exact wording but the federal government is actually prohibited from interfering in the internal running of states except for the regulation of interstate commerce.  Does this mean the US is not a single political entity?  For example, CA can have completely different regulations than NY.  Each of these states has a military force, a taxing body, a legislative body, a court system, a central budget and so on.  Is the US not a conglomaration similar to the EU?  Think of the actual definition of our country's name.  The United States of America.  Different states, united.  Not a single country but a union of various political entities.<br>
<br>
Now the nice thing about this country is that it grew to become a very cohesive single unit.  The original confederated states were very inefficient but we manageed to overcome that and grow into powerful nation.  The EU is trying to do the same thing and is facing the same problems the original union did.  Individual regions did not want to give up their independence and unique culture.  It remains to be seen if the EU can overcome these growing pains. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;"><br>
